{
  "text": "Consistent with the findings in humans, a few studies reported impaired endothelial function in the model of adjuvant-induced arthritis (AIA) in rats. In this model, endothelial dysfunction positively correlates with disease activity [CITATION_1] . However, data concerning the pathophysiological features of endothelial dysfunction are scarce. Previous studies reported that vessels from AIA rats exhibited a deficiency in tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4), the co-factor of nitric oxide synthase (NOS) [CITATION_2] and overproduced superoxide anions (O 2 -. ) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Surprisingly, whether there is an impairment of the production of endothelium-derived vasodilator factors, such as nitric oxide (NO), prostacyclin (PGI 2 ) and endotheliumderived hyperpolarizing factor (EDHF) or of contractile factors such as angiotensin-II (ANG-II), endothelin-1 (ET-1) and thromboxane A 2 (TXA 2 ) is not known. Recently, we identified the vascular arginase upregulation as a new interesting mechanism contributing to endothelial dysfunction in AIA rats [CITATION_6] .",
